<html> 
<body> 
    <h2>Javascript inhertiannce</h2>
    <p>In JavaScript, inheritance is a fundamental concept that allows one object to inherit
properties and methods from another object. This is typically achieved through prototypes. When an object is created, it can have a prototype object that serves as a template for the new object. The new object can access properties and methods defined on its prototype, allowing for code reuse and the creation of complex data structures.</p>
<p id ="details"></p> 
<script>
     class car { 
        constructor(brand) { 
            this.carname = brand; 
        
     }  
        present() { 
            return 'I have a ' + this.carname; 
        } 
    } 
    class model extends car { 
        constructor(brand, mod) { 
            super(brand); 
            this.model = mod; 
        } 
        show() { 
            return this.present() + ', it is a ' + this.model; 
        } 
    } 
    let mycar = new model("ford", "mustang");
    document.getElementById("details").innerHTML = mycar.show(); 
</script>
</body>     
</html>    